  "prompt": "Why doesn't the Government of Pakistan do anything about the situation of Karachi?",
  "response": "The situation in Karachi is complex, involving multiple challenges:\n\n1. Political fragmentation\n- Multiple political parties with competing interests\n- Lack of unified governance approach\n- Power struggles between different political groups\n\n2. Systemic issues\n- Weak administrative infrastructure\n- Corruption\n- Limited financial resources\n- Lack of long-term urban planning\n\n3. Security challenges\n- Ethnic tensions\n- Criminal activities\n- Gang violence\n- Terrorism\n\n4. Economic constraints\n- Limited budget for infrastructure development\n- High poverty rates\n- Massive urban migration\n\n5. Institutional limitations\n- Bureaucratic inefficiencies\n- Lack of comprehensive urban management strategies\n- Overlapping jurisdictions between provincial and federal authorities\n\n6. Governance problems\n- Lack of political will\n- Short-term thinking\n- Prioritizing political gains over urban development\n\n7. Complex demographic dynamics\n- Rapid population growth\n- Unplanned settlements\n- Diverse ethnic communities\n\nThese interconnected factors make addressing Karachi's challenges extremely difficult. While some improvements have been attempted, systemic issues continue to hinder comprehensive urban development and management.\n\nThe situation requires sustained, coordinated efforts from multiple stakeholders, including government, civil society, and private sector, to create meaningful change.",
